{"title_page": "Trilok Singh Chitarkar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian painter}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Trilok Singh Chitarkar\n| image            = TsaPatiala.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Trilok Singh Artist (Chitarkar) 1953\n| native_name      = \u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18 \u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a24\u0a30\u0a15\u0a3e\u0a30\n| native_name_lang = pa\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1914|12|10}}\n| birth_place      = Jartauli ([[Ludhiana District]])\n| death_date       = {{Death date|df=yes|1990|12|11}}\n| death_place      = [[Patiala]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| nationality      = [[India]]n\n| spouse           = Harbans Kaur\n| field            = Painting\n| training         = \n| alma_mater       = \n| movement         = \n| works            = \n| patrons          = \n| awards           =\n| memorials        =  Chitralok Art Gallery, [[Patiala]]\n| elected          = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.triloksinghartist.com/}}\n| bgcolour         = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Trilok Singh Chitarkar''' (1914-1990) was a versatile Indian painter. He has unique style of presenting himself through variety of themes - Sikh religion, history, culture, folk lore, love legends, portraits, social evils, nature, illustration of Gurbani, Shabads, visuals in Punjabi Encyclopedia and books<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jotinder Singh|first=Harpal Kaur|title=Guru Gobind Singh Marg as visulised by Artist Trilok Singh|publisher=www.whitefalconpublishing.com|year=2020|isbn=9789389530780|location=Chandigarh|pages=83}}<ref>. He was well versed with deep knowledge of Gurbani, history and religion. He knew many languages i.e. Gurmukhi, Punjabi, Hindi, English, Urdu, Persian, Assamese and Bengali<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jotinder Singh|first=Harpal Kaur|title=Guru Gobind Singh Marg as visulised by Artist Trilok Singh|publisher=www.whitefalconpublishing.com|year=2020|isbn=9789389530780|location=Chandigarh|pages=83}}</ref>. He translated articles from Bengali to Punjabi and published these in the book titled 'Bangla De Daab' in 1974<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jotinder Singh|first=Harpal Kaur|title=Guru Gobind Singh Marg as visulised by Artist Trilok Singh|publisher=www.whitefalconpublishing.com|year=2020|isbn=9789389530780|location=Chandigarh|pages=80}}</ref> The Artist was honoured in 1973 by the Chief Minister, Punjab, India Giani Zail Singhat a state level function organised at his residence, Chitralok, PatialaThe Artist was honoured in 1973 by the Chief Minister, [[Punjab India|Punjab]],India  Giani Zail Singh at a state level function organised at his residence, Chitralok, Patiala<ref>{{cite book|author=Ajaib Chitrakar|title=Punjabi Chitrakar|year=1995 |publisher=Publication Bureau, Punjabi University, Patiala |pages=108\u2013110}}</ref>. He is the first Punjabi Artist on whose works Ph.D. degree \"ART Of TRILOK SINGH'<ref>http://pupdepartments.ac.in/research/index.php?page=seawdcand&name=Saroj+Kumari+Sharma&department=Fine+Arts</ref> was awarded by Punjabi University , Patiala. A gold medal has been established in the name of the artist and it is awarded to the topper of M.A. Fine Arts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutartist.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist -About Artist|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.amazon.in/Guru-Gobind-Singh-Marg-visualised/dp/9389530784</ref>.\nHe was appointed as a ''State Artist'' in erstwhile [[PEPSU]] state of [[Punjab India|Punjab]] in 1948<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.punjabitribuneonline.com/2019/12/%e0%a8%b8%e0%a8%bf%e0%a9%b1%e0%a8%96-%e0%a8%87%e0%a8%a4%e0%a8%bf%e0%a8%b9%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b8-%e0%a8%a4%e0%a9%87-%e0%a8%b5%e0%a8%bf%e0%a8%b0%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b8%e0%a8%a4-%e0%a8%a6%e0%a8%be-%e0%a8%9a/|title=\u0a38\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a16 \u0a07\u0a24\u0a3f\u0a39\u0a3e\u0a38 \u0a24\u0a47 \u0a35\u0a3f\u0a30\u0a3e\u0a38\u0a24 \u0a26\u0a3e \u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a24\u0a30\u0a15\u0a3e\u0a30 \u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18|date=December 7, 2019|language=Punjabi|work=[[Punjabi Tribune]]}}</ref> and later worked as Artist in Department of Languages, Punjab.<ref>[https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/32709/12/12_chapter_6.pdf]{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> He lived and worked all over India and spent last years of his life in [[Patiala]] town in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] state in [[India]].\n\n==Personal life==\nTrilok Singh was born at village Jartauli, near [[Ludhiana]] to father Gurdit Singh and mother Daya Kaur. His father was a civil engineer by profession, who works in the [[Uganda Railway]], [[Cape Government Railways]], [[South African Republic]] and then in [[East Bengal Railways]] at [[Assam]]. His mother passed away during his childhood and he spent his childhood life at Jartauli under the supervision of his grandfather ''Baba Daya Singh Hakim''. He was married to Harbans Kaur and has one daughter and three sons.\n\n==Paintings==\n{{Expand section|date= December 2019}}\nBeing a very religious person, his knowledge about [[sikh religion]] is reflected in all his paintings.The Artist was honoured in 1973 by the Chief Minister, [[Punjab India|Punjab]],India  Giani Zail Singh at a state level function organised at his residence, Chitralok, Patiala<ref>{{cite book|author=Ajaib Chitrakar|title=Punjabi Chitrakar|year=1995 |publisher=Publication Bureau, Punjabi University, Patiala |pages=108\u2013110}}</ref>. During initial days of his career, his works mostly focused towards [[Indian independence movement|freedom struggle of India]] and [[Patriotism]]. Later on his works represented teachings of [[Guru Granth Sahib]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.punjabitribuneonline.com/c/46587101|title=Clipping of The Tribune Trust - Saturday - Satrang|website=epaper.punjabitribuneonline.com}}</ref> He also prepared illustrations of many books including ''Guru Gobind Singh Marg'', while working with Punjab Language deptt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/gurugobindmarg.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist - Guru Gobing Singh Marg|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n=== Pre Independence works ===\n[[File:Trilok Singh Chitarkar 1933.jpg|thumb|1933 - Oil painting  of Bhagat Naam Dev by Trilok Singh Chitarkar. (Chitralok Art Gallery)]]\n[[File:Trilok Singh Artist 1944.jpg|thumb|1944 - Oil Painting depicting the life of Guru Nanak in nineteen stars by Trilok Singh Chitarkar (Chitralok art Gallery)]]\n\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThen [[List of Chief Ministers of Punjab (India)|Chief Minister of Punjab]] [[Giani Zail Singh]] had inaugurated his Art Gallery ''Chitralok'', [[Patiala]] in year 1973<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutus9.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist - In Patiala|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref> and also named a street as ''Chitra-lok Street'' after him.\n\n[[Punjabi University]] has instituted an award ''Sardar Trilok Singh Chitarkar Gold Medal'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://pupdepartments.ac.in/Files/calendar/3.Calendar%20Volume%20II%20(2010)%20English%20%20(%20%20uploaded%20on%2030%20september%202011)/Calendar-Volume-II%20.pdf |title=Tuition and fees |publisher=pupdepartments.ac.in |date= |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref> in the memory of painter, which is conferred annually to university topper of [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] [[Fine Art]]. One researcher has been awarded Ph.D. degree by [[Punjabi University]] on critical work of this single painter's work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pupdepartments.ac.in/research/index.php?page=seawdcand&name=Saroj+Kumari+Sharma&department=Fine+Arts|title=Punjabi University - Research Department|website=pupdepartments.ac.in}}</ref><ref>[https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/13748/12/12_chapter%206.pdf]{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> He was mentioned in various research articles, theses<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gurmatveechar.com/books/English_Books/English_Thesis_Papers/An.Analytical.Study.of.Sikh.Calender.Art.by.Kavita.Singh.(GurmatVeechar.com).pdf |title=An analytical study of the Sikh calendar |publisher=www.gurmatveechar.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref> and books about Painters of Punjab.<ref>[http://www.aaabibliography.org/SeeMore/5022]{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> One book titled ''Chitralok's contribution to Art'' has been published in [[Punjabi language]] by Department of Languages, Punjab in year 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutus12.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist - Life Pics|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref>\n\nMany [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] newspapers share stories about the inspiring works of this artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punjabtimesusa.com/news/?p=22368|title=\u0a35\u0a1c\u0a42\u0a26-\u0a17\u0a41\u0a28\u0a4d\u0a39\u0a40 \u0a28\u0a48\u0a24\u0a3f\u0a15\u0a24\u0a3e \u0a35\u0a3e\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e\u0a15\u0a3e\u0a30 |website=Punjab Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph-media.ca/24819-9/|title=\u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a24\u0a30\u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a26\u0a40 \u0a2c\u0a47\u0a28\u0a3f\u0a06\u0a1c\u0a3c \u0a39\u0a38\u0a24\u0a40|date=August 24, 2019|website=ph-media.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypunjabtimes.com/%e0%a8%b8%e0%a8%bf%e0%a9%b1%e0%a8%96-%e0%a8%b5%e0%a8%bf%e0%a8%9a%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b0%e0%a8%a7%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b0%e0%a8%be-%e0%a8%a8%e0%a9%82%e0%a9%b0-%e0%a8%95%e0%a8%b2%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%a4%e0%a8%ae/|title=\u0a38\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a16 \u0a35\u0a3f\u0a1a\u0a3e\u0a30\u0a27\u0a3e\u0a30\u0a3e \u0a28\u0a42\u0a70 \u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e\u0a24\u0a2e\u0a3f\u0a15 \u0a30\u0a42\u0a2a \u0a26\u0a47\u0a23 \u0a35\u0a3e\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18 \u0a06\u0a30\u0a1f\u0a3f\u0a38\u0a1f &#124; :: Daily Punjab Times ::}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediapunjab.com/pages?id=9/20190815/Poad|title=MediaPunjab - \u0a16\u0a3c\u0a2c\u0a30\u0a3e\u0a02|website=www.mediapunjab.com}}</ref> The painting exhibitions of this painter have been held frequently all around the [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punjabiakhbar.com/paintings-of-guru-nanak-dev-ji-exhibition/|title=\u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18 \u0a06\u0a30\u0a1f\u0a3f\u0a38\u0a1f \u0a35\u0a71\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a02 \u0a17\u0a41\u0a30\u0a42 \u0a28\u0a3e\u0a28\u0a15 \u0a26\u0a47\u0a35 \u0a1c\u0a40 \u0a26\u0a47 \u0a2c\u0a23\u0a3e\u0a0f \u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a24\u0a30\u0a3e\u0a02 \u0a26\u0a40 \u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a2a\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a26\u0a30\u0a38\u0a3c\u0a28\u0a40 \u0a26\u0a3e \u0a09\u0a26\u0a18\u0a3e\u0a1f\u0a28 &#124; \u0a2a\u0a70\u0a1c\u0a3e\u0a2c\u0a40 \u0a05\u0a16\u0a3c\u0a2c\u0a3e\u0a30 &#124; Australia & New Zealand Punjbai News|first=Ujagar|last=Singh|date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutartist.html Detailed biography]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Artist-Trilok-Singh-457910034353744/ Facebook]\n*[https://www.amazon.in/Guru-Gobind-Singh-Marg-visualised/dp/9389530784/ Review about Artist and Life Sketch of Trilok Singh Artist]\n\n[[Category:Indian Sikhs]]\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Patiala]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian painters]]\n[[Category:Indian male painters]]\n[[Category:Painters from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Ramgarhia people]]\n\n\n{{India-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian painter}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Trilok Singh Chitarkar\n| image            = TsaPatiala.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Trilok Singh Artist (Chitarkar) 1953\n| native_name      = \u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18 \u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a24\u0a30\u0a15\u0a3e\u0a30\n| native_name_lang = pa\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1914|12|10}}\n| birth_place      = Jartauli ([[Ludhiana District]])\n| death_date       = {{Death date|df=yes|1990|12|11}}\n| death_place      = [[Patiala]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| nationality      = [[India]]n\n| spouse           = Harbans Kaur\n| field            = Painting\n| training         = \n| alma_mater       = \n| movement         = \n| works            = \n| patrons          = \n| awards           =\n| memorials        =  Chitralok Art Gallery, [[Patiala]]\n| elected          = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.triloksinghartist.com/}}\n| bgcolour         = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Trilok Singh Chitarkar''' (1914-1990) was a versatile Indian painter. He has unique style of presenting himself through variety of themes - Sikh religion, history, culture, folk lore, love legends, portraits, social evils, nature, illustration of Gurbani, Shabads, visuals in Punjabi Encyclopedia and books<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jotinder Singh|first=Harpal Kaur|title=Guru Gobind Singh Marg as visulised by Artist Trilok Singh|publisher=www.whitefalconpublishing.com|year=2020|isbn=9789389530780|location=Chandigarh|pages=83}}<ref>. He was well versed with deep knowledge of Gurbani, history and religion. He knew many languages i.e. Gurmukhi, Punjabi, Hindi, English, Urdu, Persian, Assamese and Bengali<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jotinder Singh|first=Harpal Kaur|title=Guru Gobind Singh Marg as visulised by Artist Trilok Singh|publisher=www.whitefalconpublishing.com|year=2020|isbn=9789389530780|location=Chandigarh|pages=83}}</ref>. He translated articles from Bengali to Punjabi and published these in the book titled 'Bangla De Daab' in 1974<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jotinder Singh|first=Harpal Kaur|title=Guru Gobind Singh Marg as visulised by Artist Trilok Singh|publisher=www.whitefalconpublishing.com|year=2020|isbn=9789389530780|location=Chandigarh|pages=80}}</ref>. \nThe Artist was honoured in 1973 by the Chief Minister, [[Punjab India|Punjab]],India  Giani Zail Singh at a state level function organised at his residence, Chitralok, Patiala<ref>{{cite book|author=Ajaib Chitrakar|title=Punjabi Chitrakar|year=1995 |publisher=Publication Bureau, Punjabi University, Patiala |pages=108\u2013110}}</ref>.\n He is the first Punjabi Artist on whose works Ph.D. degree \"ART Of TRILOK SINGH'<ref>http://pupdepartments.ac.in/research/index.php?page=seawdcand&name=Saroj+Kumari+Sharma&department=Fine+Arts</ref> was awarded by Punjabi University , Patiala. A gold medal has been established in the name of the artist and it is awarded to the topper of M.A. Fine Arts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutartist.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist -About Artist|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.amazon.in/Guru-Gobind-Singh-Marg-visualised/dp/9389530784</ref>.\nHe was appointed as a ''State Artist'' in erstwhile [[PEPSU]] state of [[Punjab India|Punjab]] in 1948<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.punjabitribuneonline.com/2019/12/%e0%a8%b8%e0%a8%bf%e0%a9%b1%e0%a8%96-%e0%a8%87%e0%a8%a4%e0%a8%bf%e0%a8%b9%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b8-%e0%a8%a4%e0%a9%87-%e0%a8%b5%e0%a8%bf%e0%a8%b0%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b8%e0%a8%a4-%e0%a8%a6%e0%a8%be-%e0%a8%9a/|title=\u0a38\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a16 \u0a07\u0a24\u0a3f\u0a39\u0a3e\u0a38 \u0a24\u0a47 \u0a35\u0a3f\u0a30\u0a3e\u0a38\u0a24 \u0a26\u0a3e \u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a24\u0a30\u0a15\u0a3e\u0a30 \u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18|date=December 7, 2019|language=Punjabi|work=[[Punjabi Tribune]]}}</ref> and later worked as Artist in Department of Languages, Punjab.<ref>[https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/32709/12/12_chapter_6.pdf]{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> He lived and worked all over India and spent last years of his life in [[Patiala]] town in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] state in [[India]].\n\n==Personal life==\nTrilok Singh was born at village Jartauli, near [[Ludhiana]] to father Gurdit Singh and mother Daya Kaur. His father was a civil engineer by profession, who works in the [[Uganda Railway]], [[Cape Government Railways]], [[South African Republic]] and then in [[East Bengal Railways]] at [[Assam]]. His mother passed away during his childhood and he spent his childhood life at Jartauli under the supervision of his grandfather ''Baba Daya Singh Hakim''. He was married to Harbans Kaur and has one daughter and three sons.\n\n==Paintings==\n{{Expand section|date= December 2019}}\nBeing a very religious person, his knowledge about [[sikh religion]] is reflected in all his paintings.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ajaib Chitrakar|title=Punjabi Chitrakar|year=1995 |publisher=Publication Bureau, Punjabi University, Patiala |pages=108\u2013110}}</ref> During initial days of his career, his works mostly focused towards [[Indian independence movement|freedom struggle of India]] and [[Patriotism]]. Later on his works represented teachings of [[Guru Granth Sahib]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.punjabitribuneonline.com/c/46587101|title=Clipping of The Tribune Trust - Saturday - Satrang|website=epaper.punjabitribuneonline.com}}</ref> He also prepared illustrations of many books including ''Guru Gobind Singh Marg'', while working with Punjab Language deptt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/gurugobindmarg.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist - Guru Gobing Singh Marg|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n=== Pre Independence works ===\n[[File:Trilok Singh Chitarkar 1933.jpg|thumb|1933 - Oil painting  of Bhagat Naam Dev by Trilok Singh Chitarkar. (Chitralok Art Gallery)]]\n[[File:Trilok Singh Artist 1944.jpg|thumb|1944 - Oil Painting depicting the life of Guru Nanak in nineteen stars by Trilok Singh Chitarkar (Chitralok art Gallery)]]\n\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThen [[List of Chief Ministers of Punjab (India)|Chief Minister of Punjab]] [[Giani Zail Singh]] had inaugurated his Art Gallery ''Chitralok'', [[Patiala]] in year 1973<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutus9.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist - In Patiala|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref> and also named a street as ''Chitra-lok Street'' after him.\n\n[[Punjabi University]] has instituted an award ''Sardar Trilok Singh Chitarkar Gold Medal'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://pupdepartments.ac.in/Files/calendar/3.Calendar%20Volume%20II%20(2010)%20English%20%20(%20%20uploaded%20on%2030%20september%202011)/Calendar-Volume-II%20.pdf |title=Tuition and fees |publisher=pupdepartments.ac.in |date= |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref> in the memory of painter, which is conferred annually to university topper of [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] [[Fine Art]]. One researcher has been awarded Ph.D. degree by [[Punjabi University]] on critical work of this single painter's work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pupdepartments.ac.in/research/index.php?page=seawdcand&name=Saroj+Kumari+Sharma&department=Fine+Arts|title=Punjabi University - Research Department|website=pupdepartments.ac.in}}</ref><ref>[https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/13748/12/12_chapter%206.pdf]{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> He was mentioned in various research articles, theses<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gurmatveechar.com/books/English_Books/English_Thesis_Papers/An.Analytical.Study.of.Sikh.Calender.Art.by.Kavita.Singh.(GurmatVeechar.com).pdf |title=An analytical study of the Sikh calendar |publisher=www.gurmatveechar.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref> and books about Painters of Punjab.<ref>[http://www.aaabibliography.org/SeeMore/5022]{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> One book titled ''Chitralok's contribution to Art'' has been published in [[Punjabi language]] by Department of Languages, Punjab in year 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutus12.html|title=Trilok Singh Artist - Life Pics|website=www.triloksinghartist.com}}</ref>\n\nMany [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] newspapers share stories about the inspiring works of this artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punjabtimesusa.com/news/?p=22368|title=\u0a35\u0a1c\u0a42\u0a26-\u0a17\u0a41\u0a28\u0a4d\u0a39\u0a40 \u0a28\u0a48\u0a24\u0a3f\u0a15\u0a24\u0a3e \u0a35\u0a3e\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e\u0a15\u0a3e\u0a30 |website=Punjab Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph-media.ca/24819-9/|title=\u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a24\u0a30\u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a26\u0a40 \u0a2c\u0a47\u0a28\u0a3f\u0a06\u0a1c\u0a3c \u0a39\u0a38\u0a24\u0a40|date=August 24, 2019|website=ph-media.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypunjabtimes.com/%e0%a8%b8%e0%a8%bf%e0%a9%b1%e0%a8%96-%e0%a8%b5%e0%a8%bf%e0%a8%9a%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b0%e0%a8%a7%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%b0%e0%a8%be-%e0%a8%a8%e0%a9%82%e0%a9%b0-%e0%a8%95%e0%a8%b2%e0%a8%be%e0%a8%a4%e0%a8%ae/|title=\u0a38\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a16 \u0a35\u0a3f\u0a1a\u0a3e\u0a30\u0a27\u0a3e\u0a30\u0a3e \u0a28\u0a42\u0a70 \u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e\u0a24\u0a2e\u0a3f\u0a15 \u0a30\u0a42\u0a2a \u0a26\u0a47\u0a23 \u0a35\u0a3e\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18 \u0a06\u0a30\u0a1f\u0a3f\u0a38\u0a1f &#124; :: Daily Punjab Times ::}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediapunjab.com/pages?id=9/20190815/Poad|title=MediaPunjab - \u0a16\u0a3c\u0a2c\u0a30\u0a3e\u0a02|website=www.mediapunjab.com}}</ref> The painting exhibitions of this painter have been held frequently all around the [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punjabiakhbar.com/paintings-of-guru-nanak-dev-ji-exhibition/|title=\u0a24\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a15 \u0a38\u0a3f\u0a70\u0a18 \u0a06\u0a30\u0a1f\u0a3f\u0a38\u0a1f \u0a35\u0a71\u0a32\u0a4b\u0a02 \u0a17\u0a41\u0a30\u0a42 \u0a28\u0a3e\u0a28\u0a15 \u0a26\u0a47\u0a35 \u0a1c\u0a40 \u0a26\u0a47 \u0a2c\u0a23\u0a3e\u0a0f \u0a1a\u0a3f\u0a24\u0a30\u0a3e\u0a02 \u0a26\u0a40 \u0a15\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a2a\u0a4d\u0a30\u0a26\u0a30\u0a38\u0a3c\u0a28\u0a40 \u0a26\u0a3e \u0a09\u0a26\u0a18\u0a3e\u0a1f\u0a28 &#124; \u0a2a\u0a70\u0a1c\u0a3e\u0a2c\u0a40 \u0a05\u0a16\u0a3c\u0a2c\u0a3e\u0a30 &#124; Australia & New Zealand Punjbai News|first=Ujagar|last=Singh|date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.triloksinghartist.com/aboutartist.html Detailed biography]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Artist-Trilok-Singh-457910034353744/ Facebook]\n*[https://www.amazon.in/Guru-Gobind-Singh-Marg-visualised/dp/9389530784/ Review about Artist and Life Sketch of Trilok Singh Artist]\n\n[[Category:Indian Sikhs]]\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Patiala]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian painters]]\n[[Category:Indian male painters]]\n[[Category:Painters from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Ramgarhia people]]\n\n\n{{India-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jotinder Singh", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have adjusted first paragraph.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trilok_Singh_Chitarkar"}
{"title_page": "Ron Wylie", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Ron Wylie\n| image         = \n| fullname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1933|08|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date    = \n| height        = \n| position      = [[Wing half|Right half]] / [[Inside forward]]\n| currentclub   = \n| youthyears1   =  | youthclubs1 = Clydesdale Juniors\n| youthyears2   = 1948\u20131950 | youthclubs2 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n| years1        = 1950\u20131958 | clubs1 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] | caps1 = 227 | goals1 = 35\n| years2        = 1958\u20131965 | clubs2 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] | caps2 = 196 | goals2 = 16\n| years3        = 1965\u20131970 | clubs3 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] | caps3 = 128 | goals3 = 2\n| manageryears1 = 1981\u20131982 | managerclubs1 = [[Bulova SA|Bulova]] \n| manageryears2 = 1982\u20131984 | managerclubs2 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n}}\n'''Ronald M. Wylie''' (6 August 1933 - April 14, 2020) was a Scottish former [[association football|football]] player, coach and [[Manager (football)|manager]]. He played as a [[wing half|right half]] or [[inside forward]] for [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], making more than 550 appearances in the [[English Football League|Football League]], and more than 700 in all competitions. As a manager, he took charge of [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] between 1982 and 1984.\n\n==Playing career==\nAn inside-forward, Wylie made his name at Notts County before transferring to Aston Villa in 1958. Wylie spent seven years at Aston Villa, establishing himself as the midfield schemer in the side, which won the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title and [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in the [[1959\u201360 in English football|1959\u201360 season]] and achieved [[1961 Football League Cup Final|League Cup]] success a year later. Highly regarded by the club's fans, he was not capped by [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], likely due to the abundance of quality midfielders available at the time. In 1965, he transferred to Birmingham City. Considered past his best when he made the move, he went on to play nearly 150 games for the club, was appointed club captain, and retired in 1970 at the age of 37.<ref name=Matthews>{{cite book |first=Tony |last=Matthews |title=The Encyclopedia of Birmingham City Football Club 1875-2000 |publisher=Britespot |location=Cradley Heath |year=2000 |page=136 |isbn=978-0-9539288-0-4}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nOn retirement as a player, Wylie joined the coaching staff at Aston Villa before moving to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], first as coach and later as assistant manager. He took an advisory post in [[Cyprus]] before returning to England where he was appointed manager at West Bromwich Albion in 1982.<ref name=Matthews/> With [[Ron Atkinson]] being replaced by [[Ronnie Allen]], the club had sold players such as [[Bryan Robson]], [[Remi Moses]] and [[Peter Barnes (footballer)|Peter Barnes]], leading to a decline in the club's fortunes. The side began the [[1982\u201383 in English football|1982\u201383]] season well, winning 7 of the first 11 and were in contention for a [[UEFA Cup]] place for much of the season, but a late slump in form saw them finish 11th (the last time the club finished in the top half of the top flight until the [[2011\u201312 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2011-12 season]]).\n\nThe following season, West Brom's form was mediocre although the side were always several points clear of the relegation zone. Wylie left the manager's position in February and was replaced by [[Johnny Giles]].\n\nHe returned to Aston Villa to take charge of the [[reserve team]], later working as a [[scout (sport)|scout]] before yet again rejoining Villa as community liaison officer,<ref name=Matthews/> a post which he held until retirement in 2002.<ref>{{cite news \n|url=http://www.avlfc.com/html/latest/duncan.html |title=Duncan relishes Villa job |first=Roger |last=Clarke |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=19 June 2002 |via=AVLFC.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020916035901/http://www.avlfc.com/html/latest/duncan.html |archivedate=16 September 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWylie's grandson, [[Alex Grove]], plays [[rugby union]] for [[Worcester Warriors]] and the [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland national team]]. Though born in England, Grove qualifies for Scotland through his [[Glasgow]]-born grandfather.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/scotland/6533671/Alex-Grove-owes-Scotland-debut-to-genes-of-his-grandfather-Ron-Wylie.html |title=Alex Grove owes Scotland debut to genes of his grandfather, Ron Wylie |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Alasdair |last=Reid |date=9 November 2009 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|name=Ron Wylie|id=1093}}\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/ronwylie}}\n\n{{West Bromwich Albion F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wylie, Ron}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Ron Wylie\n| image         = \n| fullname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1933|08|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date    = \n| height        = \n| position      = [[Wing half|Right half]] / [[Inside forward]]\n| currentclub   = \n| youthyears1   =  | youthclubs1 = Clydesdale Juniors\n| youthyears2   = 1948\u20131950 | youthclubs2 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n| years1        = 1950\u20131958 | clubs1 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] | caps1 = 227 | goals1 = 35\n| years2        = 1958\u20131965 | clubs2 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] | caps2 = 196 | goals2 = 16\n| years3        = 1965\u20131970 | clubs3 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] | caps3 = 128 | goals3 = 2\n| manageryears1 = 1981\u20131982 | managerclubs1 = [[Bulova SA|Bulova]] \n| manageryears2 = 1982\u20131984 | managerclubs2 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n}}\n'''Ronald M. Wylie''' (6 August 1933 - April 14, 2020) was a Scottish former [[association football|football]] player, coach and [[Manager (football)|manager]]. He played as a [[wing half|right half]] or [[inside forward]] for [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], making more than 550 appearances in the [[English Football League|Football League]], and more than 700 in all competitions. As a manager, he took charge of [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] between 1982 and 1984.\n\n==Playing career==\nAn inside-forward, Wylie made his name at Notts County before transferring to Aston Villa in 1958. Wylie spent seven years at Aston Villa, establishing himself as the midfield schemer in the side, which won the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title and [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in the [[1959\u201360 in English football|1959\u201360 season]] and achieved [[1961 Football League Cup Final|League Cup]] success a year later. Highly regarded by the club's fans, he was not capped by [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], likely due to the abundance of quality midfielders available at the time. In 1965, he transferred to Birmingham City. Considered past his best when he made the move, he went on to play nearly 150 games for the club, was appointed club captain, and retired in 1970 at the age of 37.<ref name=Matthews>{{cite book |first=Tony |last=Matthews |title=The Encyclopedia of Birmingham City Football Club 1875-2000 |publisher=Britespot |location=Cradley Heath |year=2000 |page=136 |isbn=978-0-9539288-0-4}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nOn retirement as a player, Wylie joined the coaching staff at Aston Villa before moving to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], first as coach and later as assistant manager. He took an advisory post in [[Cyprus]] before returning to England where he was appointed manager at West Bromwich Albion in 1982.<ref name=Matthews/> With [[Ron Atkinson]] being replaced by [[Ronnie Allen]], the club had sold players such as [[Bryan Robson]], [[Remi Moses]] and [[Peter Barnes (footballer)|Peter Barnes]], leading to a decline in the club's fortunes. The side began the [[1982\u201383 in English football|1982\u201383]] season well, winning 7 of the first 11 and were in contention for a [[UEFA Cup]] place for much of the season, but a late slump in form saw them finish 11th (the last time the club finished in the top half of the top flight until the [[2011\u201312 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2011-12 season]]).\n\nThe following season, West Brom's form was mediocre although the side were always several points clear of the relegation zone. Wylie left the manager's position in February and was replaced by [[Johnny Giles]].\n\nHe returned to Aston Villa to take charge of the [[reserve team]], later working as a [[scout (sport)|scout]] before yet again rejoining Villa as community liaison officer,<ref name=Matthews/> a post which he held until retirement in 2002.<ref>{{cite news \n|url=http://www.avlfc.com/html/latest/duncan.html |title=Duncan relishes Villa job |first=Roger |last=Clarke |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=19 June 2002 |via=AVLFC.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020916035901/http://www.avlfc.com/html/latest/duncan.html |archivedate=16 September 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWylie's grandson, [[Alex Grove]], plays [[rugby union]] for [[Worcester Warriors]] and the [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland national team]]. Though born in England, Grove qualifies for Scotland through his [[Glasgow]]-born grandfather.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/scotland/6533671/Alex-Grove-owes-Scotland-debut-to-genes-of-his-grandfather-Ron-Wylie.html |title=Alex Grove owes Scotland debut to genes of his grandfather, Ron Wylie |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Alasdair |last=Reid |date=9 November 2009 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|name=Ron Wylie|id=1093}}\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/ronwylie}}\n\n{{West Bromwich Albion F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wylie, Ron}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "AngryHarpy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "