{"title_page": "Wendell Phillips Stafford", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name          = Wendell Phillips Stafford\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image         = Wendell Phillips Stafford by C. M. Bell.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| office        = Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]]\n| term_start    = June 1, 1904\n| term_end      = May 4, 1931\n| nominator     =\n| appointer     = [[List of federal judges appointed by Theodore Roosevelt|Theodore Roosevelt]]\n| predecessor   = [[Jeter Connelly Pritchard]]\n| successor     = [[F. Dickinson Letts]]\n| office1       = [[List of justices of the Vermont Supreme Court|Associate Justice]] of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]]\n| term_start1   = 1900\n| term_end1     = 1904\n| predecessor1  = [[Laforrest H. Thompson]]\n| successor1    = [[George M. Powers]]\n| office2       = Member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] from [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]]\n| term_start2   = 1892\n| term_end2     = 1894\n| predecessor2  = Francis Walker\n| successor2    = John Calvin Clark\n| pronunciation =\n| birth_name    = Wendell Phillips Stafford\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1861|05|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Barre (city), Vermont|Barre]], [[Vermont]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1953|04|21|1861|05|01}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| death_cause   =\n| resting_place = Mount Pleasant Cemetery<br>[[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]], [[Vermont]]\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship   =\n| nationality   =\n| party         =\n| otherparty    =\n| height        =\n| spouse        =\n| partner       =\n| relations     =\n| children      =\n| parents       =\n| mother        =\n| father        =\n| relatives     =\n| residence     =\n| education     = [[Boston University School of Law]] {{midsize|([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])}}\n| alma_mater    =\n| occupation    =\n| profession    =\n| known_for     =\n| salary        =\n| net_worth     =\n| cabinet       =\n| committees    =\n| portfolio     =\n| awards        =\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes     =\n}}\n'''Wendell Phillips Stafford''' (May 1, 1861 \u2013 April 21, 1953) was an American [[Attorneys in the United States|attorney]] and jurist. He was most notable for his service as an [[List of justices of the Vermont Supreme Court|Associate Justice]] of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]] and as an [[United States federal judge|Associate Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in [[Barre (city), Vermont|Barre]], [[Vermont]], Stafford was the son of Franklin Stafford and Sarah (Noyes) Stafford. He attended the public schools of Barre and graduated from [[Barre Academy]] in 1878.<ref>\"[https://vermonthistory.org/documents/findaid/Barre%20Academy.pdf Barre Academy Collection, 1852-1891, BHC 9-11]\", ''Barre History Collection'', via ''vermonthistory.org''.</ref> Stafford graduated from [[St. Johnsbury Academy]] in 1880, and received a [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1883.<ref name=\"auto\">{{FJC Bio|2263|nid=1388191|name=Wendell Phillips Stafford<!--(1861\u20131953)-->}}</ref> He was admitted to the bar, and began to practice in [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]], Vermont in partnership with [[Henry Clay Ide]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TrzfAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+barre#v=onepage&q=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+barre&f=false|title=The Poets' Lincoln: Tributes in Verse to the Martyred President|first=Osborn Hamiline|last=Oldroyd|date=2 April 2019|publisher=The editor|via=Google Books|page=236}}</ref> Among the prospective attorneys who studied law in their office was [[William H. Taylor (judge)|William H. Taylor]], who later served as an Associate Justice of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cummings |first=Charles R. |date=November 1906 |title=The New Judiciary System: The Board of Superior Judges; William H. Taylor |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zN5EAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA296 |magazine=The Vermonter |location=White River Junction, VT |publisher=Chas. R. Cummings |page=296 |ref={{sfnRef|\"The New Judiciary System\"}}}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nStafford was a member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] in 1892.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was a Reporter of Decisions for the Supreme Court of Vermont from 1896 to 1900.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was an associate justice of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]] from 1900 to 1904, succeeding [[Laforrest H. Thompson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R7oTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT50&dq=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives#v=onepage&q=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives&f=false|title=The Court-house of the District of Columbia|first1=Francis Regis|last1=Noel|first2=Mrs Margaret Brent Burke|last2=Downing|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Press of Judd & Detweiler, Incorporated|via=Google Books|page=77}}</ref> He resigned to accept appointment as a federal judge, and was succeeded by [[George M. Powers]].<ref>{{cite news |date=June 4, 1904 |title=Judge George M. Powers |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/197234664/ |work=Burlington Free Press |location=Burlington, VT |url-access=subscription |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Federal judicial service==\n\nStafford received a [[recess appointment]] from President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] on June 1, 1904, to an Associate Justice seat on the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]] (now the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]) vacated by Associate Justice [[Jeter Connelly Pritchard]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was nominated to the same position by President Roosevelt on December 6, 1904.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on December 13, 1904, and received his commission the same day.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/vermontgreenmou00crocgoog|quote=wendell phillips stafford appointed judge 1904.|title=Vermont: The Green Mountain State|year=1921|first=Walter Hill|last=Crockett|publisher=Century history Company, Incorporated|via=Internet Archive|page=[https://archive.org/details/vermontgreenmou00crocgoog/page/n477 373]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/georgetownunive01easbgoog|quote=stafford, wendell phillips.|title=Georgetown University in the District of Columbia, 1789-1907: Its Founders, Benefactors, Officers, Instructors and Alumni|year=1907|first=James Stanislaus|last=Easby-Smith|publisher=Lewis Publishing Company|via=Internet Archive|page=[https://archive.org/details/georgetownunive01easbgoog/page/n323 275]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZRhUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vTkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4361,2213375&dq=wendell+phillips+stafford&hl=en|title=The Philadelphia Record - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|page=857}}</ref> His service terminated on May 4, 1931, due to his retirement.<ref>Beacon Lights of Literature, published by Iroquois Publishing Co., Syracuse, Book 9, 1940, page 857</ref>\n\n===Other service===\n\nStafford was a Professor at [[George Washington University]] in 1908.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=X1wiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA498&dq=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives#v=onepage&q=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives&f=false|title=Catalogue of Officers and Students of Middlebury College in Middlebury, Vermont: And of Others who Have Received Degrees, 1800-1915|first=Middlebury|last=College|date=2 April 2019|publisher=The College|via=Google Books|page=498}}</ref>\n\n==Career as author==\n\nStafford was also a poet, and his published works include: ''North Flowers'' (1902); ''Dorian Days'' (1909); and ''The Land We Love'' (1916).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7dA_AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet#v=onepage&q=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet&f=false|title=North Flowers...: A Few Poems|first=Wendell Phillips|last=Stafford|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Press of the Caledonian Company|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PIkXAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet#v=onepage&q=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet&f=false|title=Dorian Days: Poems|first=Wendell Phillips|last=Stafford|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Macmillan|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/landwelovepoems00stafgoog|quote=Wendell Phillips Stafford poet.|title=The Land We Love: Poems, Chiefly Patriotic|year=1916|first=Wendell Phillips|last=Stafford|publisher=A. F. Stone|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Death and burial==\n\nStafford died at his home in [[Washington, D.C.]] on April 21, 1953.<ref>The Journal of the Bar Association of the District of Columbia, published by the association, Volume 20, 1953, page 276</ref> He was buried at Mount Pleasant Cemetery in St. Johnsbury.<ref>Report of Proceedings of the Annual Meeting, published by Vermont Bar Association, 1954, page 50</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nIn 1886, Stafford married Florence S. Goss of St. Johnsbury.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} They were the parents of two sons, Edward, a Washington, DC attorney and Robert, who died as a child.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FJC Bio|2263|nid=1388191|name=Wendell Phillips Stafford<!--(1861\u20131953)-->}}\n* {{Findagrave|142087226}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Wendell Phillips Stafford}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeter Connelly Pritchard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]]}}|years=1904\u20131931}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[F. Dickinson Letts]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stafford, Wendell Phillips}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:United States district court judges appointed by Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:People from Barre, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Caledonia County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name          = Wendell Phillips Stafford\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image         = Wendell Phillips Stafford by C. M. Bell.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| office        = Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]]\n| term_start    = June 1, 1904\n| term_end      = May 4, 1931\n| nominator     =\n| appointer     = [[List of federal judges appointed by Theodore Roosevelt|Theodore Roosevelt]]\n| predecessor   = [[Jeter Connelly Pritchard]]\n| successor     = [[F. Dickinson Letts]]\n| office1       = [[List of justices of the Vermont Supreme Court|Associate Justice]] of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]]\n| term_start1   = 1900\n| term_end1     = 1904\n| predecessor1  = [[Laforrest H. Thompson]]\n| successor1    = [[George M. Powers]]\n| office2       = Member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] from [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]]\n| term_start2   = 1892\n| term_end2     = 1894\n| predecessor2  = Francis Walker\n| successor2    = John Calvin Clark\n| pronunciation =\n| birth_name    = Wendell Phillips Stafford\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1861|05|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Barre (city), Vermont|Barre]], [[Vermont]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1953|04|21|1861|05|01}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| death_cause   =\n| resting_place = Mount Pleasant Cemetery<br>[[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]], [[Vermont]]\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship   =\n| nationality   =\n| party         =\n| otherparty    =\n| height        =\n| spouse        =\n| partner       =\n| relations     =\n| children      =\n| parents       =\n| mother        =\n| father        =\n| relatives     =\n| residence     =\n| education     = [[Boston University School of Law]] {{midsize|([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])}}\n| alma_mater    =\n| occupation    =\n| profession    =\n| known_for     =\n| salary        =\n| net_worth     =\n| cabinet       =\n| committees    =\n| portfolio     =\n| awards        =\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes     =\n}}\n'''Wendell Phillips Stafford''' (May 1, 1861 \u2013 April 21, 1953) was a [[Vermont]] [[Attorneys in the United States|attorney]] and jurist. He was most notable for his service as an [[List of justices of the Vermont Supreme Court|Associate Justice]] of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]] and as an [[United States federal judge|Associate Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in [[Barre (city), Vermont|Barre]], [[Vermont]], Stafford was the son of Franklin Stafford and Sarah (Noyes) Stafford. He attended the public schools of Barre and graduated from [[Barre Academy]] in 1878.<ref>\"[https://vermonthistory.org/documents/findaid/Barre%20Academy.pdf Barre Academy Collection, 1852-1891, BHC 9-11]\", ''Barre History Collection'', via ''vermonthistory.org''.</ref> Stafford graduated from [[St. Johnsbury Academy]] in 1880, and received a [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1883.<ref name=\"auto\">{{FJC Bio|2263|nid=1388191|name=Wendell Phillips Stafford<!--(1861\u20131953)-->}}</ref> He was admitted to the bar, and began to practice in [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]], Vermont in partnership with [[Henry Clay Ide]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TrzfAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+barre#v=onepage&q=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+barre&f=false|title=The Poets' Lincoln: Tributes in Verse to the Martyred President|first=Osborn Hamiline|last=Oldroyd|date=2 April 2019|publisher=The editor|via=Google Books|page=236}}</ref> Among the prospective attorneys who studied law in their office was [[William H. Taylor (judge)|William H. Taylor]], who later served as an Associate Justice of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cummings |first=Charles R. |date=November 1906 |title=The New Judiciary System: The Board of Superior Judges; William H. Taylor |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zN5EAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA296 |magazine=The Vermonter |location=White River Junction, VT |publisher=Chas. R. Cummings |page=296 |ref={{sfnRef|\"The New Judiciary System\"}}}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nStafford was a member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] in 1892.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was a Reporter of Decisions for the Supreme Court of Vermont from 1896 to 1900.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was an associate justice of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]] from 1900 to 1904, succeeding [[Laforrest H. Thompson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R7oTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT50&dq=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives#v=onepage&q=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives&f=false|title=The Court-house of the District of Columbia|first1=Francis Regis|last1=Noel|first2=Mrs Margaret Brent Burke|last2=Downing|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Press of Judd & Detweiler, Incorporated|via=Google Books|page=77}}</ref> He resigned to accept appointment as a federal judge, and was succeeded by [[George M. Powers]].<ref>{{cite news |date=June 4, 1904 |title=Judge George M. Powers |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/197234664/ |work=Burlington Free Press |location=Burlington, VT |url-access=subscription |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Federal judicial service==\n\nStafford received a [[recess appointment]] from President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] on June 1, 1904, to an Associate Justice seat on the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]] (now the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]) vacated by Associate Justice [[Jeter Connelly Pritchard]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was nominated to the same position by President Roosevelt on December 6, 1904.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on December 13, 1904, and received his commission the same day.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/vermontgreenmou00crocgoog|quote=wendell phillips stafford appointed judge 1904.|title=Vermont: The Green Mountain State|year=1921|first=Walter Hill|last=Crockett|publisher=Century history Company, Incorporated|via=Internet Archive|page=[https://archive.org/details/vermontgreenmou00crocgoog/page/n477 373]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/georgetownunive01easbgoog|quote=stafford, wendell phillips.|title=Georgetown University in the District of Columbia, 1789-1907: Its Founders, Benefactors, Officers, Instructors and Alumni|year=1907|first=James Stanislaus|last=Easby-Smith|publisher=Lewis Publishing Company|via=Internet Archive|page=[https://archive.org/details/georgetownunive01easbgoog/page/n323 275]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZRhUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vTkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4361,2213375&dq=wendell+phillips+stafford&hl=en|title=The Philadelphia Record - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|page=857}}</ref> His service terminated on May 4, 1931, due to his retirement.<ref>Beacon Lights of Literature, published by Iroquois Publishing Co., Syracuse, Book 9, 1940, page 857</ref>\n\n===Other service===\n\nStafford was a Professor at [[George Washington University]] in 1908.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=X1wiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA498&dq=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives#v=onepage&q=%22wendell+phillips+stafford%22+vermont+house+of+representatives&f=false|title=Catalogue of Officers and Students of Middlebury College in Middlebury, Vermont: And of Others who Have Received Degrees, 1800-1915|first=Middlebury|last=College|date=2 April 2019|publisher=The College|via=Google Books|page=498}}</ref>\n\n==Career as author==\n\nStafford was also a poet, and his published works include: ''North Flowers'' (1902); ''Dorian Days'' (1909); and ''The Land We Love'' (1916).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7dA_AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet#v=onepage&q=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet&f=false|title=North Flowers...: A Few Poems|first=Wendell Phillips|last=Stafford|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Press of the Caledonian Company|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PIkXAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet#v=onepage&q=%22Wendell+Phillips+Stafford%22+poet&f=false|title=Dorian Days: Poems|first=Wendell Phillips|last=Stafford|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Macmillan|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/landwelovepoems00stafgoog|quote=Wendell Phillips Stafford poet.|title=The Land We Love: Poems, Chiefly Patriotic|year=1916|first=Wendell Phillips|last=Stafford|publisher=A. F. Stone|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Death and burial==\n\nStafford died at his home in [[Washington, D.C.]] on April 21, 1953.<ref>The Journal of the Bar Association of the District of Columbia, published by the association, Volume 20, 1953, page 276</ref> He was buried at Mount Pleasant Cemetery in St. Johnsbury.<ref>Report of Proceedings of the Annual Meeting, published by Vermont Bar Association, 1954, page 50</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nIn 1886, Stafford married Florence S. Goss of St. Johnsbury.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} They were the parents of two sons, Edward, a Washington, DC attorney and Robert, who died as a child.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FJC Bio|2263|nid=1388191|name=Wendell Phillips Stafford<!--(1861\u20131953)-->}}\n* {{Findagrave|142087226}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Wendell Phillips Stafford}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeter Connelly Pritchard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]]}}|years=1904\u20131931}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[F. Dickinson Letts]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stafford, Wendell Phillips}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:United States district court judges appointed by Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:People from Barre, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Caledonia County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n", "name_user": "Genarians", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wendell_Phillips_Stafford"}
{"title_page": "Cracklin' Rosie", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Cracklin' Rosie\n| cover      = Cracklin_Rosie.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| album      = [[Tap Root Manuscript]]\n| B-side     = Lordy\n| released   = August 1970\n| format     = [[7\" single|7\"]] 45 RPM\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 2:54\n| label      = [[Uni Records|Uni]]\n| writer     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| producer   = [[Tom Catalano]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Cracklin' Rosie'''\" is a song written and [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] by [[Neil Diamond]] in 1970, with instrumental backing by L.A. session musicians from the [[The Wrecking Crew (music)|Wrecking Crew]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Kent |last=Hartman |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749/page/261 261\u2013263] |year=2012 |title=The Wrecking Crew |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749 |url-access=registration |publisher=[[St. Martin's Press|St. Martin\u2019s Griffin]] |isbn=978-1-250-03046-7}}</ref> including [[Hal Blaine]] on drums, [[Larry Knechtel]] on keyboards, [[Joe Osborn]] on bass, [[Al Casey (rock guitarist)|Al Casey]] on guitar and [[Gene Estes]] on percussion - arranged by [[Don Randi]], and was included on his album ''[[Tap Root Manuscript]]''.  In October 1970;<ref name=\"jackson\"/> the song became Diamond's first American #1 hit on The Billboard Hot 100, and his third to [[Platinum record|sell a million copies]].<ref name=\"jackson\"/> It was his breakthrough single on the UK Singles Chart, reaching #3 for four weeks in November and December. ''Billboard'' ranked the record as the No. 17 song of 1970.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1970]]</ref> It also reached #2 on both the Australian Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1970/19701205.html |title=Go-Set Australian charts - 5 December 1970 |publisher=Poparchives.com.au |date=1970-12-05 |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> and the Irish Singles Chart. Its best performance was in New Zealand, where it stayed at number one for 5 weeks at the end of the year.<ref>The official New Zealand music chart;RIANZ website</ref>\n\nThe single version released by [[Uni Records]] was in mono, while the album version from ''Tap Root Manuscript'' was in stereo.\n\n==Song meaning==\nMarried to a catchy and dynamic melody and arrangement, the lyrics suggested to some a devotion to a woman of the night:<ref name=\"jackson\" />\n\n{{Quote|<poem>Oh, I love my Rosie child \u2014\nYou got the way to make me happy.\n'You and me, we go in style ...\nCracklin' Rose, you're a store bought woman\nBut you make me sing like a guitar hummin' ...</poem>}}\n\nThe stories about how Diamond was inspired to write the song are apocryphal. \"Crackling Ros\u00e9\" is the name of an inexpensive sparkling [[wine]] once manufactured by Andres Wines of British Columbia, Canada, popular among the indigent population. One story suggests Diamond heard a story about a [[First Nations|native Canadian]] tribe while doing an interview in Toronto, Canada&mdash;the tribe had more men than women, so the lonely men of the tribe would sit around the fire and drink their wine together&mdash;which inspired him to write the song.<ref name=\"jackson\">{{cite book | last=Jackson | first=Laura | url=http://www.laurajacksonbooks.com | title=Neil Diamond: His Life, His Music, His Passion | publisher=[[ECW Press]] | year=2005 | isbn=1-55022-707-6}} pp. 70\u201371.</ref> Another is that he saw homeless men drinking Crackling Rose while on tour in western Canada. \n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Belgium \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Germany \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|2|song=Cracklin' Rosie|accessdate=January 14, 2018}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Single Top 100]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1970 |publisher= [[Single Top 100]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= February 25, 2018 |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1970&cat=s |language= nl}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qartistid=661#n_view_location |title=Flavour of New Zealand |website= |date=1970-12-21 |accessdate=2017-01-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(D).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|3|artist=Neil Diamond }}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Neil Diamond }}\n|-\n|US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/music/Neil-Diamond/chart-history/adult-contemporary \"Neil Diamond Chart History (Easy Listening)\".] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19701017.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, October 17, 1970]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |title=Forum - 1970 (ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts) |website=Australian-charts.com |accessdate=2018-01-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602084720/http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |archivedate=2016-10-20}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3740&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3740.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3740|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|Netherlands <ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1970 |publisher= [[Single Top 100]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= February 25, 2018 |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1970&cat=s |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|62\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1970|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1970.html|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>[http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1970.htm Musicoutfitters.com]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Easy Listening<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/45_list_view_record.php?li=2162]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1970YESP.html |title=Cash Box Year-End Charts: Top 100 Pop Singles, December 26, 1970 |access-date=January 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722145703/https://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1970YESP.html |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|neil-diamond|cracklin-rosie}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Neil Diamond singles}}\n\n[[Category:1970 songs]]\n[[Category:1970 singles]]\n[[Category:Neil Diamond songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Neil Diamond]]\n[[Category:Songs about alcohol]]\n[[Category:Uni Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Cracklin' Rosie\n| cover      = Cracklin_Rosie.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| album      = [[Tap Root Manuscript]]\n| B-side     = Lordy\n| released   = August 1970\n| format     = [[7\" single|7\"]] 45 RPM\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 2:54\n| label      = [[Uni Records|Uni]]\n| writer     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| producer   = [[Tom Catalano]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Cracklin' Rosie'''\" is a song written and [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] by [[Neil Diamond]] in 1970, with instrumental backing by L.A. session musicians from the [[The Wrecking Crew (music)|Wrecking Crew]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Kent |last=Hartman |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749/page/261 261\u2013263] |year=2012 |title=The Wrecking Crew |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749 |url-access=registration |publisher=[[St. Martin's Press|St. Martin\u2019s Griffin]] |isbn=978-1-250-03046-7}}</ref> including [[Hal Blaine]] on drums, [[Larry Knechtel]] on keyboards, [[Joe Osborn]] on bass, [[Al Casey (rock guitarist)|Al Casey]] on guitar and [[Gene Estes]] on percussion - arranged by [[Don Randi]], and was included on his album ''[[Tap Root Manuscript]]''.  In October 1970;<ref name=\"jackson\"/> the song became Diamond's first American #1 hit on The Billboard Hot 100, and his third to [[Platinum record|sell a million copies]].<ref name=\"jackson\"/> It was his breakthrough single on the UK Singles Chart, reaching #3 for four weeks in November and December. ''Billboard'' ranked the record as the No. 17 song of 1970.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1970]]</ref> It also reached #2 on both the Australian Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1970/19701205.html |title=Go-Set Australian charts - 5 December 1970 |publisher=Poparchives.com.au |date=1970-12-05 |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> and the Irish Singles Chart. Its best performance was in New Zealand, where it stayed at number one for 5 weeks at the end of the year.<ref>The official New Zealand music chart;RIANZ website</ref>\n\nThe single version released by [[Uni Records]] was in mono, while the album version from ''Tap Root Manuscript'' was in stereo.\n\n==Song meaning==\nMarried to a catchy and dynamic melody and arrangement, the lyrics suggested to some a devotion to a woman of the night:<ref name=\"jackson\" />\n\n{{Quote|<poem>Oh, I love my Rosie child \u2014\nYou got the way to make me happy.\n'You and me, we go in style ...\nCracklin' Rose, you're a store bought woman\nBut you make me sing like a guitar hummin' ...</poem>}}\n\nCracklin' Rosie is actually a type of [[wine]]. Diamond heard a story about a [[First Nations|native Canadian]] tribe while doing an interview in Toronto, Canada&mdash;the tribe had more men than women, so the lonely men of the tribe would sit around the fire and drink their wine together&mdash;which inspired him to write the song.<ref name=\"jackson\">{{cite book | last=Jackson | first=Laura | url=http://www.laurajacksonbooks.com | title=Neil Diamond: His Life, His Music, His Passion | publisher=[[ECW Press]] | year=2005 | isbn=1-55022-707-6}} pp. 70\u201371.</ref>\n\nThe title has also been interpreted to be a misspelling of a [[ros\u00e9]] wine which is \"crackling\"&mdash;a U.S. term equivalent to [[Petillant#Semi-sparkling wines|p\u00e9tillant]] or lightly sparkling.<ref>''The New Wine Lover's Companion'', 2nd edition, by Ron Herbst and Sharon Tyler Herbst, published by Barron's Educational Series, Inc.</ref>\n\nMany Diamond fans have traditionally believed the crackling wine he was referring to was Sparkling Mateus Rose, a medium-quality, low-priced artificially carbonated wine favored by college students on the West Coast of the U.S. during the late 1960s and early 1970s, or Richards Wild Irish Rose, an alcoholic beverage produced by Centerra Wine Company, which is part of the Constellation Brands organization.{{citation needed |date=August 2018}}\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Belgium \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Germany \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|2|song=Cracklin' Rosie|accessdate=January 14, 2018}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Single Top 100]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1970 |publisher= [[Single Top 100]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= February 25, 2018 |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1970&cat=s |language= nl}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qartistid=661#n_view_location |title=Flavour of New Zealand |website= |date=1970-12-21 |accessdate=2017-01-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(D).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|3|artist=Neil Diamond }}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Neil Diamond }}\n|-\n|US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/music/Neil-Diamond/chart-history/adult-contemporary \"Neil Diamond Chart History (Easy Listening)\".] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19701017.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, October 17, 1970]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |title=Forum - 1970 (ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts) |website=Australian-charts.com |accessdate=2018-01-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602084720/http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |archivedate=2016-10-20}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3740&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3740.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3740|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|Netherlands <ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1970 |publisher= [[Single Top 100]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= February 25, 2018 |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1970&cat=s |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|62\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1970|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1970.html|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>[http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1970.htm Musicoutfitters.com]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Easy Listening<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/45_list_view_record.php?li=2162]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1970YESP.html |title=Cash Box Year-End Charts: Top 100 Pop Singles, December 26, 1970 |access-date=January 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722145703/https://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1970YESP.html |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|neil-diamond|cracklin-rosie}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Neil Diamond singles}}\n\n[[Category:1970 songs]]\n[[Category:1970 singles]]\n[[Category:Neil Diamond songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Neil Diamond]]\n[[Category:Songs about alcohol]]\n[[Category:Uni Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Dmenigma", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSong meaning:Identified correct wine as the source material for the song. Don't know how to insert links!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cracklin%27_Rosie"}
{"title_page": "William J. Walker", "text_new": "{{short description|United States Army major general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = William J. Walker\n| birth_date    = \n| death_date    = \n| image         = Maj. Gen. William J. Walker Official Photo.jpg\n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|United States of America}}\n| branch        = {{army|USA}}\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n| unit          = \n| battles       = [[Afghanistan]]\n| commands      = {{plainlist|\n*District of Columbia National Guard\n*DCNG Land Component Command\n*Joint Task Force-District of Columbia\n*Partnership for the Americas\n*Company A, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion\n }}\n| awards        = {{plainlist|\n*[[U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n*[[Legion of Merit]]\n*[[Bronze Star]]\n*[[Meritorious Service Medal]]\n*[[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n}}\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = [[Special Agent]], retired, [[Drug Enforcement Administration]]\n| website       = http://www.dc.ng.mil\n}}\n\n'''William J. Walker''' is a [[United States Army]] [[major general (United States)|major general]], and the Commanding General of the [[District of Columbia National Guard]]. He<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dod.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1459953/general-officer-announcements/#.XJ05wPomlzc.email|title=General Officer Announcements, 2018}}</ref> is responsible for the command and control of the District of Columbia Army and Air National Guard units with an authorized strength of 2,700 Soldiers and Airmen. Walker is retired from civilian federal service as a career special agent of the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] where he was promoted to the [[Senior Executive Service (United States)]] a General Officer equivalent rank in January 2003.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Education==\n\nWalker is a native of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], where he was born and raised. Walker attended St. Sabina private Catholic grammar school as a youth and graduated from [[Leo Catholic High School]] in 1975.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url= http://www.leoalumni.org/william-j-walker-75-promoted-to-brigadier-general-of-d-c-army-national-guard/|title= William J. Walker \u201975, promoted to Brigadier General of D.C. Army National Guard|publisher= Leo High School|accessdate= January 16, 2018}}</ref> Walker attended the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] where he earned a bachelor of arts degree. He then attended [[Chicago State University]], where he earned his master of science degree in Criminal Justice and Corrections.<ref name=\"nationalguard.mil\">{{cite web|url= http://www.nationalguard.mil/portals/31/Features/ngbgomo/bio/2/2394.html|title= Walker Bio|publisher=National Guard Bureau|accessdate= March 2, 2018}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> In addition, Walker holds a master of science degree in Strategic Intelligence from the [[National Intelligence University]] and also a master of arts degree in International Service from [[American University]]. Walker has also attended and completed the National and International Security Program for senior executives at the Kennedy School of Government at [[Harvard University]], the National Security Studies Program at [[George Washington University]] and the Seminar XXI Foreign Politics, International Relations and the National Interest Fellowship at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"Patch\"/>\n\n==Military career==\n[[File:BG Walker with Brig Gen Bozard presenting award to Capt Morgan.jpg|thumb|left|Brig. Gen. William J. Walker, D.C. National Guard and Brig. Gen. Jeffery C. Bozard, Commander, 113th Wing, present Capt. John Morgan the Brigadier General Howard W. Kacy Flying Safety Award.]]\n\nWalker was commissioned as [[Military Police]] [[2nd Lieutenant]] assigned to the 50th Military Police Company, Somerset, [[New Jersey]] in May 1985. Since then, Walker has served as Commander, Alpha Company, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion; Commander, Land Component Command, District of Columbia Army National Guard; Chief of Staff, District of Columbia National Guard; Deputy Commander \u2013 Army, Joint Task Force, and Commander, Partnership for the Americas, Brigade Joint Task Force\u2013Jamaica; Commander, Mobilization Augmentation Command, District of Columbia Army National Guard.<ref name=\"nationalguard.mil\"/>\n[[File:Dr. Mark T. Esper, 23rd Secretary of the Army with MG Walker and BG Dean.jpg|alt=|thumb|Secretary of the Army Dr. Mark T. Esper attends and speaks at the 2018 D.C. National Guard Military Ball, Washington, D.C., May 5, 2018.]]\nWalker was called to serve with the U.S. Army in September 2001 immediately following the [[September 11 attacks]]. He was part of [[Operation Noble Eagle]]  and was an operations officer in the Pentagon. He later served with the [[NATO]] [[International Security Assistance Force]] and at the [[Embassy of the United States, Kabul]].<ref name=\"Patch\">{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Andy|title=William J. Walker promoted to Brigadier General of District of Columbia, Army National Guard|url=https://patch.com/district-columbia/georgetown/william-j-walker-promoted-brigadier-general-district-columbia-army-national-guard|publisher=Georgetown, DC Patch|accessdate=2 April 2018|date=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, he was appointed as the Commander, Land Component Command, District of Columbia National Guard and subsequently promoted to Brigadier General in November 2015.\n\nDuring the 2017 Presidential Inauguration, Walker commanded the Joint Task Force-District of Columbia (JTF-DC) which deployed nearly 8,000 National Guard personnel, from 43 states and territories, to support security, traffic control, and crowd management during the [[Inauguration of Donald Trump]]. JTF-DC supported seven, federal and D.C. agencies during the presidential inauguration. National Guard personnel helped monitor the 248 traffic, access and security points, and blocking positions along the National Mall and parade route. The support provided by National Guard personnel enabled the [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] to respond to 217 arrests, and the [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department]] to conduct 229 responses, 94 hospital transports and numerous medical tent treatments.&nbsp;The D.C. National Guard has supported 40 presidential inaugurations since 1861.\n\nOn January 20, 2017, Walker assumed the role of acting Commanding General, District of Columbia Army and Air National Guard, nicknamed the \u201cCapitol Guardians\u201d. On March 2018, President Donald J. Trump nominated Walker for the promotion to Major General and selected him as the Commanding General.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.dvidshub.net/news/222457/dc-national-guard-welcomes-new-commanding-general |title= D.C. National Guard welcomes new Commanding General|publisher= Defense Video Imagery Distribution System |accessdate= February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://dc.ng.mil/History/Command/CG/Pages/default.aspx|title= BRIGADIER GENERAL WILLIAM J. WALKER Commanding General, District of Columbia|publisher= D.C. National Guard|accessdate= January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Assignments==\n* May 1985 \u2013 September 1987, Platoon Leader, 50th Military Police Company, Somerset, [[New Jersey]]\n* September 1987 \u2013 December 1989, Signal Officer, 250th Signal Battalion, Plainfield, New Jersey\n* December 1989 \u2013 December 1990, Counterintelligence Officer, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, [[Miami]], [[Florida]]\n* December 1990 \u2013 April 1993, Team Chief, All-source intelligence, Alpha Company, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* April 1993 \u2013 April 1994, Battalion Security Officer, S-2, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* April 1994 \u2013 May 1996, Commander, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* May 1996 \u2013 November 1996, Plans Officer, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* December 1996 \u2013 September 1997, MOS Support Officer, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* September 1997 \u2013 December 1999, Commander, Alpha Company, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* December 1999 \u2013 September 2001, Operations Officer / Branch Chief, Mobilization Augmentation Detachment, [[Washington, District of Columbia|Washington]], [[District of Columbia]]\n* September 2001 \u2013 February 2002, Operations Officer, Headquarters, Department of the Army, Army Operations Center, [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]], [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Virginia]]\n* February 2002 \u2013 January 2005, Operations Officer, Headquarters, Department of the Army, Army Crisis Action Team, Pentagon, Arlington, Virginia,\n* January 2005 \u2013 April 2008, Division Chief, Mobilization Augmentation Command, duty at the National Military Command Center, Pentagon, Arlington, Virginia\n* August 2005 \u2013 June 2006, Student, [[Inter-American Defense College]], [[Fort McNair]], Washington, District of Columbia\n* April 2008 \u2013 November 2008, J \u22122 Vice, Intelligence Directorate, [[National Guard Bureau]], (Mobilization Augmentation Command-Detail) Arlington, Virginia\n* November 2008 \u2013 July 2009, Commander, Partnership for the Americas, Brigade Joint Task Force \u2013 [[Jamaica]], Washington, DC and [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n* July 2009 \u2013 June 2010, J \u22122 Vice, Intelligence Directorate, National Guard Bureau, (Mobilization Augmentation Command-Detail) Arlington, Virginia\n* June 2010 \u2013 October 2011, Chief of Staff, District of Columbia Army National Guard, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia\n* October 2011 \u2013 June 2012, Chief, Theater Observation Detachment \u2013 Afghanistan, & Senior [[International Security Assistance Force]] Liaison Officer, Center for Army Lessons Learned, [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]]\n* November 2011 \u2013 June 2012, Senior Military Strategist, Office of Transition Management, Embassy Kabul (Concurrent assignment), Kabul, Afghanistan\n* June 2012 \u2013 March 2013, Chief of Staff, District of Columbia Army National Guard, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia\n* March 2013 \u2013 March 2015, Commander, Mobilization Augmentation Command, Washington, District of Columbia\n* April 2015 \u2013 January 2017, Commanding General, Land Component Command, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia\n* January 2017 \u2013 present,  Commanding General, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia<ref name=\"nationalguard.mil\"/>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n||[[File:U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|106px|border]]\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Bronze Star]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] with four oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Commendation Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Force Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Air Force Commendation Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Us jointservachiev rib.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Joint Service Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=8|type=oak|ribbon=Army Reserve Achievement ribbon.svg|108px}}\n|Army Reserve Components Achievement Medal with 1 silver oak leaf cluster and 3 bronze oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award-3d.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Superior Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=DoS MHA.svg|width=106}}\n|Department of State [[Meritorious Honor Award]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Afghanistan Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Humanitarian Service ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Outstanding Volunteer Service ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Military Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:AFRM with Hourglass Device (gold) and 2 M devices.jpg|106px]]\n|[[Armed Forces Reserve Medal]] with [[Hourglass device]] and 2 [[Mobilization device]]s\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Army Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Overseas Service Ribbon]] \n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Army Reserve Overseas Training Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|Reserve Components Overseas Training Military Ribbon\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|width=106}}\n|[[NATO Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army Staff Identification Badge.png|100px]]\n|[[Army Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:USFOR-A Shoulder Insignia.jpg|100px|USFOR-A Shoulder Insignia]]\n|[[U.S. Forces Afghanistan Combat Service Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Dates of promotions==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Promotions\n! Insignia !! Rank !! Date\n|-\n||[[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|35px]]||[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]||June 28, 2018\n|-\n||[[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|20px]]||[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]||November 25, 2015\n|-\n||[[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|25px]]||[[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]||September 29, 2006\n|-\n||[[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|20px]]||[[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]||March 10, 2003\n|-\n||[[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|20px]]||[[Major (United States)|Major]]||January 13, 1998\n|-\n||[[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|15px]]||[[Captain (United States)|Captain]]||November 18, 1990\n|-\n||[[File:US-OF1A.svg|6px]]||[[First Lieutenant (United States)|First Lieutenant]]||April 19, 1988\n|-\n||[[File:US-OF1B.svg|6px]]||[[Second lieutenant#United States|Second Lieutenant]]||April 20, 1985<ref>National Guard Bureau, Biographical sketch, William J. Walker</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Civilian Service ==\n\n<br />\n\n[[File:General William J. Walker.jpg|thumb|Special Agent William J Walker, DEA, Retired, bio photo]]\nWalker is the former Vice Chairman, Board of Directors of the [[Young Marines]], a military affiliated non-profit service organization for boys and girls ages eight through high school that provides developmental programs that nurtures and encourages its over 10,000 members into becoming responsible citizens who enjoy a positive and drug-free lifestyle. Walker is a member of [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] and [[Sigma Pi Phi]] fraternities.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nWalker concurrently serves as the Director of the District of Columbia National Guard and is a member of the Headquarters Department of the Army Senior Executive Service.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dc.ng.mil/About-Us/State-Partnership-Program/|title=DCNG Partnership Program|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n<br /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dc.ng.mil/Components/|title=The District of Columbia National Guard|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>{{Authority control}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcmilitary.com/dc_military_mag/features/dcng-celebrates--year-history-of-the-u-s-army/article_d64a600b-09f6-5e2b-85eb-81981e50c04f.html|title=WO's 100-year celebration|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, William J.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Chicago State University alumni]]\n[[Category:National Intelligence University alumni]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:National Guard of the United States generals]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|United States Army major general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = William J. Walker\n| birth_date    = \n| death_date    = \n| image         = Maj. Gen. William J. Walker Official Photo.jpg\n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|United States of America}}\n| branch        = {{army|USA}}\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n| unit          = \n| battles       = [[Afghanistan]]\n| commands      = {{plainlist|\n*District of Columbia National Guard\n*DCNG Land Component Command\n*Joint Task Force-District of Columbia\n*Partnership for the Americas\n*Company A, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion\n }}\n| awards        = {{plainlist|\n*[[U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n*[[Legion of Merit]]\n*[[Bronze Star]]\n*[[Meritorious Service Medal]]\n*[[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n}}\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = [[Special Agent]], retired, [[Drug Enforcement Administration]]\n| website       = http://www.dc.ng.mil\n}}\n\n'''William J. Walker''' is a [[United States Army]] [[major general (United States)|major general]], and the Commanding General of the [[District of Columbia National Guard]]. He<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dod.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1459953/general-officer-announcements/#.XJ05wPomlzc.email|title=General Officer Announcements, 2018}}</ref> is responsible for the command and control of the District of Columbia Army and Air National Guard units with an authorized strength of 2,700 Soldiers and Airmen. Walker is retired from civilian federal service as a career special agent of the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] where he was promoted to the [[Senior Executive Service (United States)]] a General Officer equivalent rank in January 2003.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Education==\n\nWalker is a native of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], where he was born and raised. Walker attended St. Sabina private Catholic grammar school as a youth and graduated from [[Leo Catholic High School]] in 1975.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url= http://www.leoalumni.org/william-j-walker-75-promoted-to-brigadier-general-of-d-c-army-national-guard/|title= William J. Walker \u201975, promoted to Brigadier General of D.C. Army National Guard|publisher= Leo High School|accessdate= January 16, 2018}}</ref> Walker attended the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] where he earned a bachelor of arts degree. He then attended [[Chicago State University]], where he earned his master of science degree in Criminal Justice and Corrections.<ref name=\"nationalguard.mil\">{{cite web|url= http://www.nationalguard.mil/portals/31/Features/ngbgomo/bio/2/2394.html|title= Walker Bio|publisher=National Guard Bureau|accessdate= March 2, 2018}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> In addition, Walker holds a master of science degree in Strategic Intelligence from the [[National Intelligence University]] and also a master of arts degree in International Service from [[American University]]. Walker has also attended and completed the National and International Security Program for senior executives at the Kennedy School of Government at [[Harvard University]], the National Security Studies Program at [[George Washington University]] and the Seminar XXI Foreign Politics, International Relations and the National Interest Fellowship at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"Patch\"/>\n\n==Military career==\n[[File:BG Walker with Brig Gen Bozard presenting award to Capt Morgan.jpg|thumb|left|Brig. Gen. William J. Walker, D.C. National Guard and Brig. Gen. Jeffery C. Bozard, Commander, 113th Wing, present Capt. John Morgan the Brigadier General Howard W. Kacy Flying Safety Award.]]\n\nWalker was commissioned as [[Military Police]] [[2nd Lieutenant]] assigned to the 50th Military Police Company, Somerset, [[New Jersey]] in May 1985. Since then, Walker has served as Commander, Alpha Company, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion; Commander, Land Component Command, District of Columbia Army National Guard; Chief of Staff, District of Columbia National Guard; Deputy Commander \u2013 Army, Joint Task Force, and Commander, Partnership for the Americas, Brigade Joint Task Force\u2013Jamaica; Commander, Mobilization Augmentation Command, District of Columbia Army National Guard.<ref name=\"nationalguard.mil\"/>\n[[File:Dr. Mark T. Esper, 23rd Secretary of the Army with MG Walker and BG Dean.jpg|alt=|thumb|Secretary of the Army Dr. Mark T. Esper attends and speaks at the 2018 D.C. National Guard Military Ball, Washington, D.C., May 5, 2018.]]\nWalker was called to serve with the U.S. Army in September 2001 immediately following the [[September 11 attacks]]. He was part of [[Operation Noble Eagle]]  and was an operations officer in the Pentagon. He later served with the [[NATO]] [[International Security Assistance Force]] and at the [[Embassy of the United States, Kabul]].<ref name=\"Patch\">{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Andy|title=William J. Walker promoted to Brigadier General of District of Columbia, Army National Guard|url=https://patch.com/district-columbia/georgetown/william-j-walker-promoted-brigadier-general-district-columbia-army-national-guard|publisher=Georgetown, DC Patch|accessdate=2 April 2018|date=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, he was appointed as the Commander, Land Component Command, District of Columbia National Guard and subsequently promoted to Brigadier General in November 2015.\n\nDuring the 2017 Presidential Inauguration, Walker commanded the Joint Task Force-District of Columbia (JTF-DC) which deployed nearly 8,000 National Guard personnel, from 43 states and territories, to support security, traffic control, and crowd management during the [[Inauguration of Donald Trump]]. JTF-DC supported seven, federal and D.C. agencies during the presidential inauguration. National Guard personnel helped monitor the 248 traffic, access and security points, and blocking positions along the National Mall and parade route. The support provided by National Guard personnel enabled the [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] to respond to 217 arrests, and the [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department]] to conduct 229 responses, 94 hospital transports and numerous medical tent treatments.&nbsp;The D.C. National Guard has supported 40 presidential inaugurations since 1861.\n\nOn January 20, 2017, Walker assumed the role of acting Commanding General, District of Columbia Army and Air National Guard, nicknamed the \u201cCapitol Guardians\u201d. On March 2018, President Donald J. Trump nominated Walker for the promotion to Major General and selected him as the Commanding General.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.dvidshub.net/news/222457/dc-national-guard-welcomes-new-commanding-general |title= D.C. National Guard welcomes new Commanding General|publisher= Defense Video Imagery Distribution System |accessdate= February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://dc.ng.mil/History/Command/CG/Pages/default.aspx|title= BRIGADIER GENERAL WILLIAM J. WALKER Commanding General, District of Columbia|publisher= D.C. National Guard|accessdate= January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Assignments==\n* May 1985 \u2013 September 1987, Platoon Leader, 50th Military Police Company, Somerset, [[New Jersey]]\n* September 1987 \u2013 December 1989, Signal Officer, 250th Signal Battalion, Plainfield, New Jersey\n* December 1989 \u2013 December 1990, Counterintelligence Officer, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, [[Miami]], [[Florida]]\n* December 1990 \u2013 April 1993, Team Chief, All-source intelligence, Alpha Company, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* April 1993 \u2013 April 1994, Battalion Security Officer, S-2, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* April 1994 \u2013 May 1996, Commander, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* May 1996 \u2013 November 1996, Plans Officer, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* December 1996 \u2013 September 1997, MOS Support Officer, HHC, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* September 1997 \u2013 December 1999, Commander, Alpha Company, 260th Military Intelligence Battalion, Miami, Florida\n* December 1999 \u2013 September 2001, Operations Officer / Branch Chief, Mobilization Augmentation Detachment, [[Washington, District of Columbia|Washington]], [[District of Columbia]]\n* September 2001 \u2013 February 2002, Operations Officer, Headquarters, Department of the Army, Army Operations Center, [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]], [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Virginia]]\n* February 2002 \u2013 January 2005, Operations Officer, Headquarters, Department of the Army, Army Crisis Action Team, Pentagon, Arlington, Virginia,\n* January 2005 \u2013 April 2008, Division Chief, Mobilization Augmentation Command, duty at the National Military Command Center, Pentagon, Arlington, Virginia\n* August 2005 \u2013 June 2006, Student, [[Inter-American Defense College]], [[Fort McNair]], Washington, District of Columbia\n* April 2008 \u2013 November 2008, J \u22122 Vice, Intelligence Directorate, [[National Guard Bureau]], (Mobilization Augmentation Command-Detail) Arlington, Virginia\n* November 2008 \u2013 July 2009, Commander, Partnership for the Americas, Brigade Joint Task Force \u2013 [[Jamaica]], Washington, DC and [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n* July 2009 \u2013 June 2010, J \u22122 Vice, Intelligence Directorate, National Guard Bureau, (Mobilization Augmentation Command-Detail) Arlington, Virginia\n* June 2010 \u2013 October 2011, Chief of Staff, District of Columbia Army National Guard, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia\n* October 2011 \u2013 June 2012, Chief, Theater Observation Detachment \u2013 Afghanistan, & Senior [[International Security Assistance Force]] Liaison Officer, Center for Army Lessons Learned, [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]]\n* November 2011 \u2013 June 2012, Senior Military Strategist, Office of Transition Management, Embassy Kabul (Concurrent assignment), Kabul, Afghanistan\n* June 2012 \u2013 March 2013, Chief of Staff, District of Columbia Army National Guard, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia\n* March 2013 \u2013 March 2015, Commander, Mobilization Augmentation Command, Washington, District of Columbia\n* April 2015 \u2013 January 2017, Commanding General, Land Component Command, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia\n* January 2017 \u2013 present,  Commanding General, Joint Forces Headquarters, Washington, District of Columbia<ref name=\"nationalguard.mil\"/>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n||[[File:U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|106px|border]]\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Bronze Star]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] with four oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Commendation Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Force Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Air Force Commendation Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Us jointservachiev rib.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Joint Service Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=8|type=oak|ribbon=Army Reserve Achievement ribbon.svg|108px}}\n|Army Reserve Components Achievement Medal with 1 silver oak leaf cluster and 3 bronze oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award-3d.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[Army Superior Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-oak|ribbon=DoS MHA.svg|width=106}}\n|Department of State [[Meritorious Honor Award]]